I am back in my village in Greece in the summertime. I am walking with my little sister, my dress flapping in the wind and my flip flops in my hands so I can walk through the water and feel the sand and rocks on my feet. As I abandon the sea and walk up towards a pathway, Fifi, a stray beach dog I have known since she was a puppy, recognizes me and runs up to me. I pet her, she is happy, I am happy, and I sit on the pathway in the sun to pet her.

I am getting in my car at 7:00 am with my sister driving the same roads we drive everyday to get to school. I see all my friends and classmates walking in. I sit in my first period seat tired but also happy. I talk to my friends and enjoy their company in class. I repeat this 6 more times till its 2:00.

I am hanging out with all my best friends at a bar. We are all drinking and having a blast. We close the bar down and end up back at my house. We get Taco Bell on the way home and when we get back to my house and start listening to music and laughing/ singing to the music. We were all happy to be there and just enjoy the moment.

i am leaving my last class of the day and head straight to mrs. franco's office to fill out scholarship applications for college. we make small talk and she offers me  random snack she has in her fridge. i often get distracted and repeatedly get on my phone which she teases me about. then, my friend walks in and sits down next to me. we then start talking and joking around. lunch rolls around and we debate on whether we should grab lunch. my last class of the day is some people's 3rd period, so i was always at school doing nothing for the next couple of hours, just waiting for my mom to pick me up.

I am sitting in my car driving and listening to music. I pull into a nice looking house, with dogs running around and a basketball hoop in the driveway. I park next to the garage, enter the code, and make my way upstairs. When I enter the room, I see all my friends already there, watching a youtube on the tv. I greet them and sit down on the couch. We all begin to get into an argument about something stupid. After we settle it, we go downstairs and eat dinner. Then, we all go back upstairs and decide what we are going to do that night. Once we have it figured out, we hop into my friend's Jeep and drive off.

I am walking into a nice quiet restaurant with all my friend. We find the seat in the corner and sit down. When we ready to order, the waitress come without wearing the mask. She smiled at us and ask how we are doing and we greet her back. We the food come we happily enjoyed it without concerning about the people that pass by us.
I am watching myself study for school. I am sitting in my desk in my room

I can remember senior year, sitting in class as the rumors started to spread about a two week break due to COVID. We were all excited, we needed a break and looked forward to our senior activities that would follow in the weeks to come. I remember being happy to be sent home and never thought of senior year being cut short and missing out on everything we looked forward to.

I met someone after I had just gotten out of a long relationship. We met when I was in quarantine. He blinked his flashlight on his phone at me through his dorm window, and I saw. When I got out, I met him in a parking garage. It was warm out, so we stayed out till late in the evening. We talked about life. We have so much in common.

I miss being able to just walk into a store without a mask and not have to worry about COVID. I would walk in with my kids and my husband and we'd look around. I miss all the smells of fresh cookies from the bakery and popcorn at the movies.

I pack into the car and drive about 30 minutes to the concert. We all get out of the car and sit in the bed of the truck drinking. We wave and talk to the cars around us, meeting new people as they walk by. When the concert is about to start we squeeze into lines to have our tickets checked and then the mass of people pile onto the grass to watch. It is like sardines packed into a can, holding hands with my friends to not lose them in the mass. The music is blaring and everyone is jumping and dancing together.

I pulled up to my friend's house late on a Saturday night. We had all gotten back from homecoming that night and we were looking forward to having a good time throughout the rest of the night. I walked in the door and found that everyone was already down in the basement playing a video game. As the night went on, my friend decided to bring out the booze they had stored. I had never been drunk before, so I was unaware what it was going to be like, but my friends and I drank and played several games together until we were drunk. I would walk around and talk to the people who were there, even if I had no idea who they were. It was great.

I remember before the pandemic it was my boyfriends birthday. Me and my friends and all of his friends got together with his family to plan a surprise party last minute and when the day finally came, it was the best surprise ever. He didn't expect it at all and his reaction was priceless. We listened to music with everyone and there was so much food that his mom had made. It was a perfect night and we all had so much fun. Even though it was about a year ago, we all still bring up memories from that day and I can't wait for more big gatherings and parties to be able to celebrate things like birthdays and holidays.

I say later to my partner in crime at work, hop into my car, seatbelt on--music on, and sit for a second. I tilt my head back and close my eyes before a small sigh lets out then I'm on my way. I wonder by some people have such bright headlights as my eyes become blinded in such a dark area where I live at. Due to the day of the week I head to my partners house instead of my own, and am greeted at the door with a smile and eyes full of love. I hear my other friends in the background laughing. I go to change into some comfy, and think about my mom and sister at home before returning to the living room where everyone is seated. Snacks and soda await as we start the scary movie. The lights go out to set the spooky mood and I close my eyes for a second.
I see multiple people in the gym all dribbling basket balls. While I walk in to see my friends tying their shoes while I say hi to all of them.

I wake up at 8am on the weekend. OSU is playing a noon game against Indiana. I wake up extra early to ensure that I will be able to start grouping up with friends to hang out before the game. It was a nice cool breeze and I was in a group of many people standing next to each other tailgating the game.

I walk to the restaurant with my arms heavy with winter clothing. I have no mask on, but instead have a scarf around my nose and mouth to keep my warm. I walk in and see my family waiting inside for me there, and the rest of my family walks in from behind me and joins them at the dining table reserved for us.

I was in chemistry class. We didn't really have any work to do, so everyone was just hanging out and talking with each other. Some of us were on our phones, some were drawing on the white board, and others were playing cards. My teacher was cool, so we were talking to him a good bit about sports and such. I really liked that class because in moments like that we could just do whatever and had no work or anything to worry about.
i was lying against the fence

I was standing behind the block at one of the biggest meets of the season. I look to my left to see spectators packed into bleachers, sitting shoulder to shoulder, dripping sweat from the humidity that surrounds the pool. I look over to the official as he blows the whistle, my turn, I think. I look to my right to see our rival school, preparing to smoke everyone. We hear the whistle that signals for us to step up on the blocks. Once I’m standing on the block, I look to the opposite end of the pool to see my entire team standing their ready to cheer me on. Next thing I know, the sound goes off and I’m in the water. Swimming until my body hurts, with everything I’ve got left. The only thing I hear is the murmurs of people screaming from above the water...

I was taking my economic class final exam. The sound of pencils writing and whispers filled the room. We were all focused on the exams and the question being asked and had no clue we would not return to school later on.

I was younger playing with my friend named Tony. we were playing basketball and this older kid around pushed me down and my friend Tony punched him in the face,. all of our parents started yelling at echoer and mine and Tonys fought the other gentleman and it was a weird thing to see at a young age. it taught me how to be a man and the type of man I wanted to be when I grew up. I remember I was so bad at basketball now I'm on scholarship here so I guess that was some motivation to do better and be better so I wasn't pushed around. idk what I'm saying really but hope this helps I need to eat dinner so I'm rushing.

I went on a trip with my sister the week before COVID shut everything down. She had a week off work so we decided to go to Vermont because I had wanted to go for awhile. During our trip we found a neat coffee shop that was also inside of a book store. The shop was relatively lively filled with friendly conversation and children running around the store. My sister and I sat at a table drinking our fresh coffee and splitting several baked goods whilst we each read our books. It was a serene setting and one I often long for nowadays.

I went to Europe with my best friend back in March, and the first city we went to was Prague. We stayed in a really cool hostel, they offered us beer as soon as we came in and we grabbed some out of the fridge. We were taken up to our room and met about 5 people who were already up there. They were really nice and fun people from England. We all decided to go out and do a pub crawl together, and as the night went on my friend and I demonstrated our own British accents to them, which they were rather impressed by. The night was full of dancing, fun conversation, and new friends.
I went to my friends house and there were about 8 of us playing basketball together. We also went out for pizza afterwards and had a fun time listening to music on the drive to and from.

I would leave school after 6th period every day, and go home for an hour, usually to eat snacks and sometimes nap. I napped too long and was late a few times. I would then drive back to school and practice on the field, playing with a lot of my friends on the team. On game days I would usually be home for longer, and then go to school to play or get on the bus to another school. I just miss the fun of playing sports with my friends and how normal life was.

Im sitting at a lunch table, its 9th-period study hall. Im by myself at the table. Im bored so I'm looking around the room a lot. I pull out some homework and start doing it, it's math homework that I enjoy doing. I feel satisfied once I finished the bulk of it. Now the period is ending and we have to put the chairs up on the tables. I do this to my table and the tables around me and now I wait a few minutes for the bell to ring. I can remember the piled black softball hoodie I was wearing, I have jeans on. I wait in the lobby by the door for my boyfriend to pass so I can see him.
Im standing in a moshpit full of people at a concert. Everyone is jumping and having a great time. The arena is dark, but the lights from the show are very bright. The music is very loud
in bathroom holding hair back, loud noises outside, people walking past me.

It is my senior year of high school, and my boys and I are performing in the swim cadet show. Basically we are just dancing around the pool and performing funny skits. This particular skit is a boxing match between me and my best friend. We enter the "ring" while laughing because it is so funny to us. We exchange fake punches, and then he knocks me out into the pool and the crowd goes wild.

It was a Saturday night after Ohio State football just won against Penn State at home. I rushed the field with my teammates and after the game we went and got food and chilled in my dorm room. Later we got ready to go to Formal, a party for the cross country team at the cross country house. I remember going and taking pictures and dancing all night.

It was a Sunday with nothing but blue in the sky. My dad and I were on the way home to a sports bar that we would watch football games at. Once we got home, we grabbed our leftover pizzas, threw on our Green Bay Packers jerseys, and watched the football game. My dad was born in Green Bay so whenever the Packers win, it's a party in the house. They won on that Sunday and then a few of my friends came over and we all ate dinner and talked about the games that day.

It was loud and people were surrounding me. I was at a fundraiser event that went from 7pm to 7am. To keep people awake, they held a dance party where thousands of us were jumping up and down. I was laughing, making eye contact with my friends who were also laughing. We were all happy. Like really happy. Our legs hurt from jumping and we were constantly being pushed around because there were so many people on a small dance floor. We didn't care. It was fun because there were so many people. Everyone was feeling the same way I was. I was screaming the lyrics to every song at the top of my lungs. I should have been tired but I was feeding off the energy of everyone else.

It was my friend's birthday, so we all hopped in the car and drove 2 hours west to the beach. This was right before COVID entered the USA and destroyed our way of life. First, we stopped at a restaurant called Camp 19, well known for their breakfast in Oregon. Next, we went to a trail and decided to hike up it, and hopefully see the Oregon coast's beautiful view. Sadly we couldn't make it all the way up due to the weather; the heavy rains made it extremely. Muddy. We walked back to the car and decided to go to the beach. It has been ages since any of us went to the beach, so we ran at the excitement of seeing the shoreline. After the beach, we went back home and partied, to celebrate my friend turning 18.

It was my last day in New York before I'd come here for my first semester. I went to Washington Square Park, in Manhattan, just as I had done almost everyday before, except really early to hear this jazz ensemble that plays there every morning. They were amazing. Everyone around the park was so happy. My friends came later, I stayed with them until the very last train out at 12:30AM. They walked me to the station, hugged me goodbye, and spent me off. I've never had a happier day.

Last December I went to a concert with three of my cousins at the Quicken Loans Arena in Cleveland, Ohio. There were thousands of people there and the stadium was almost filled. Every one was super close together, dancing and singing. Once the concert ended, everyone left the arena at once and it was packed. It took at least 30 minutes to get out because of how many people were there.

Me and my friends would go to Walmart at 2 am and mess around in the store. We would play hide and seek within the stores and we would walk around for hours for snacks and fun crafts to do. We would aslo sit in the parking lot for hours and talk about life and just hang out late at night with each other. Now we cant do this due to the stores closing early because of covid.

My dad and I were sitting in the pent house suite at the United center in Chicago, Illinois. It was the NBA all star game in February of 2020. We watched as the all star players name's were called and they ran out onto the court. My dad and I both had the same drink - a vodka water with a lime. We left the suite to go get food. As we were walking to the elevator we saw a large figure. He turned around and we were able to identify him as NBA legend Dikembe Mutombo. He looked at my dad and my dad gave him his patented finger wag which he returned. We returned to the suite to watch the final quarter of the game, in which team Lebron scored 24 points to win.

My friend and I went to new york city for new years. I remember the streets were filled with people who were joyful and excited for the new year. Everyone was in a good mood, there seemed to be no worries at all. I remember thinking how cool it was to be in a city filled with so many people who were so joyful. a few short months after that coronavirus hit. This memory is one that it vividly stuck in my mind

My friend and I went to New York over spring break right before the pandemic. I remember walking around lower manhattan and west village, shopping at so many different stores and eating a lot of good food. As I was walking around the city, I saw so much opportunity for me and want to live there when I’m older. I loved the energy and the vibe the city gave off.
My friends and I are standing on the bleachers at a football game cheering our team on. We are winning 24-21 after just scoring two touchdowns in the last minutes of the fourth quarter.

My Nan and I would walk from her house in England into town to the market. As soon as you got there, you could see the cathedral cross in the center of the market, with four alleys separating from it, full of streets. We would go to Waterstones, a book store, grab a coffee and a bite to eat, and dive into the books finding our favorite ones. We would then wonder around the clothing stores, grab some groceries, and head home happily for the day to make tea.

On christmas my now husband and I sat next to one another and opened gifts. Including my parents, my brother, and two dogs. There was wrapping paper everywhere and my dog was playing in it. It was warmer outside I think for ohio. I remember being sad because we never know when it is my dad's last anything because he has terminal cancer. And I think it even snowed a little that day. Christmas is hard for me, but I remember that day being really good and warm. And great now I'm crying.

Pizza crust is what comes to mind as my father and fell fond of it in the early days of the outbreak. As our relationship grew Stronger and that with my mother began to slowly die, he began to lean more on his lust for crust
Racing with my friends (closed track). After our time is up, we go out to a bar for food and drinks.
school students teachers classroom desk whiteboard homework

Sitting at crowded tables eating away at traditions not caring about anything or anyone just how much food I would be able to eat. Start people-watching and wondering if I would see a friendly face I could talk to

Sweaty bodies were pushing each other around while everyone around me, myself included, sang at the top of their lungs. We all push ourselves closer to the stage as Uzi got ready to stage dive into the crowd. A feeling of euphoria rushed over me as I was caught up in the moment thinking that life couldn't get any better than this one night. My hand grazes his shirt as he floats through the crowd while XO Tour Lif3 is being blasted through the speakers. My friends and I look at each other as though we all knew we would speak of this moment at school the next day nonstop. The rush of a concert on a school night at HOB is unmatched.

The dismissal  bell just. I get in the crowded hall and somehow I immediately make eye contact with my friend Mark. He smirks and proceeds to start to running and pushing people to get down the school steps. I run after him because I am pretty sure we are racing to get to the parking lot. By the time I get there, Mark and 2 of my other friends are already in the car. I get in and we argue about where to go to eat before the football game.

The event I pictured was when I was playing rugby with some of the guys I knew from the football team the summer before college. After the game we went to Buffalo Wild Wings and watched sports while eating in a big group. The place was lively and packed on a Saturday. We had to talk loudly and talked about the game we had won among other things.

The memory that comes to mind is one of a high school football game from my senior year. We were playing our rival team, and the student section was overflowing with fans from our school - everyone had dressed for the theme, was hugging and laughing, and cheering as loud as they could for our team to win. I remember jumping up and down with my friends in the front rows of the section, everyone linking arms and screaming our fight song whenever we'd get a first down or a touchdown, or whenever we felt like cheering for our school. The night was filled with laughter, stadium popcorn, and people around every corner.

The time was clocking out and all the girls on the team started to get excited.  She looked over at the sideline to see her family and friends cheering in a huge crowd.  Then the buzzer sounded, she ran over to her teammates where they all started to jump up and down and hug with happiness. They had just made history as a team, they had just won a state championship.

The week before lockdown me and my 3 best friends had a really fun sleepover. We watched a movie in my friends basement and even played video games on her virtual reality headset. We all laughed so hard that night playing card games and it was the most fun I had in a while.
we all left school that day with the intention on coming back very soon. We were all clueless to what was to lie ahead. School has changed for everyone

We are in Nationwide Arena, and we got a bunch of discounted hockey tickets to see the Blue Jackets game. There are plenty of people with popcorn and jerseys on. There are people chanting. My family and friends take up quite a bit of space in the middle section of the stands.

We are walking to the stadium where Ohio State football plays. My group of seven as well as hundreds of other students and families walk together talking and enjoying the beautiful weather, excited too watch the game. We get in line for them to take our tickets, go through security, find our seats and begin to chant to the songs playing before the game. After each touchdown we cheer and scream with happiness as a big group.

We were all laughing and having a good time. I was playing games with my friends and enjoying their company. It was a pretty big group. Everyone was so happy, I could have stayed there forever. It was dark in the house and we had music playing on the speaker. Some people were dancing to the music, while others sat and watched, and some continued to play games. I loved getting to enjoy their company.

We won grand champs at our last show choir and everybody screamed and celebrated, rushing the stage. Everyone in the crew, pit band, and singer/dancers was jumping together and cheering. The directors were as happy as the students, jumping and cheering. Everyone was so close. No cares in the world. The only feelings were joy and excitement. Finally everyone on stage would calm down, and we would take pictures together to remember this moment forever. Only at that point no one knew it would probably be their last time being able to perform like this in a long while, or even be able to be in such a big wonderful group.

When I first walked into the main event room, my eyes lit up. I was so excited to see all of the decorations set up for my sister's special day. The night started with pictures of my sister and our family. When the guests started to arrive I could already tell that this night was going to be special. I spent most of my time with my friends that I invited, but whenever I got the chance to dance or spend time with my sister it was a lot of fun. As the night continued I just didn't want it to end. All of the people we love were all in the same room for the same reason, to celebrate the bat mitzvah of my youngest sister. It was a night that I will never forget.
